  "opinion": "As a 71-year-old carpenter from Rome, I've seen many changes in the world, but the rise of fake content on social media is something that troubles me deeply, even though I only spend a few times monthly on these platforms. My perspective is shaped by a lifetime of working with my hands, building things that are real and sturdy, and by my faith in Islam, which teaches the importance of truth and integrity. When I encounter fake content, it feels like a crack in the foundation of trust that holds society together, much like a poorly crafted joint in a piece of furniture that can lead to collapse over time. To manage this issue, I believe in a practical, hands-on approach. First, I rely on my own judgment and experience. Just as I can tell good wood from bad by its grain and texture, I've learned to spot fake content by checking the source, looking for inconsistencies, and considering whether it aligns with what I know to be true from my years of living in Rome and observing the world. I don't rush to share anything; instead, I take my time to verify, much like I measure twice and cut once in my carpentry work. Second, I think it's important to talk about these things with my family and friends. As a married man with two children, I've always valued open conversations, and we discuss what we see online to help each other stay informed and avoid misinformation. My hobbies in classical music and painting remind me that beauty and truth often go hand in hand, and I try to apply that sensibility to social media by seeking out content that is uplifting and genuine. Finally, I support efforts by social media companies to remove fake content, but I also believe that individuals have a responsibility to be cautious and not spread falsehoods. In my view, dealing with fake content is about building a culture of honesty, one post at a time, just as I build furniture piece by piece, ensuring each part is solid and true.",
